Time Complexity:

Let n = number of nodes in linked list

    Reverse list → O(n)
    Traversal with filtering → O(n)
    Reverse again → O(n)

Overall: O(n)


Space Complexity:

    No extra data structures used (only pointers)

Overall: O(1)


Approach:

1. Reverse the linked list:
   - So we can process from right → left (original order)

2. Traverse the reversed list:
   - Maintain current node (temp)
   - Compare with next nodes

3. For each node:
   - Skip all nodes having smaller values than current node
   - Link current node to next greater/equal node

4. Move forward and repeat

5. After processing entire list:
   - Reverse the list again to restore original order

6. Return final head









class Solution {
    public ListNode reverse(ListNode head) {
        ListNode curr = head;
        ListNode prev = null;
        ListNode fwd = null;
        while (curr != null) {
            fwd = curr.next;
            curr.next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = fwd;
        }
        return prev;
    }

    public ListNode removeNodes(ListNode head) {
        head = reverse(head);
        ListNode temp = head;
        ListNode nextNode = null;
        while(temp!=null){
            nextNode = temp.next;
            while(nextNode!=null && temp.val>nextNode.val){
                nextNode = nextNode.next;
            }
            temp.next = nextNode;
            temp=temp.next;
        }
        return reverse(head);
    }
}
